Today is #InternationalWomensDay, a day in March (which is Women's History Month) set aside to honor women and to celebrate women's achievement, raise awareness against bias, and take action for equality. It follows Black History Month, which should mean that Black women have a whole two-month spotlight where their long lists of efforts and contributions to society are amplified. It should be two months of society reflecting on how new realities can be shaped by those who come from identities that have long been marginalized, because a system led by/created for those communities works for everyone. However, that isn't the case. When it comes to history, the story of women, particularly Black women is largely one of exclusion, silence, absence and bias
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
If you look around, weâ€™re facing a lesson that history has tried to teach us so many times in so many ways. Over and over weâ€™ve been reminded to â€œlisten to Black women.â€ Over and over again history shows a pattern of white people (including white women) and yes, even men of color co-opting, using and discarding their energy and investment instead of supporting their role as leaders
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Over and over again, Iâ€™ve seen examples of the silencing of Black women in many different ways like the """armor""" (read lack of accountability and privilege) that being white can afford someoneâ€™s social platform. As Jenn M. Jackson says, "I am reminded how so much of what I remember is rooted in the erasure of darker-skinned, poor and working-class, queer, and trans black women who contributed significant work to make this country a freer place."
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Time after time we forget or willingly push aside the call, and since we donâ€™t learn, history repeats itself. So letâ€™s do some learning. Check out the link in bio to take a walk through a historical timeline, to listen to the voices/quotes of Black women, and to learn from past mistakes, paying attention to the examples of what happens when women speak up and the benefits that are possible when Black women lead
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Note: These are only a few examples, this is not an exhaustive list. I encourage you to do your own research and add your own evidence

This is a post about a journey, but not one of the outdoor adventures that youâ€™ll see me post about from time to time.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
In a culture that has historically stigmatized the public discussion of mental health, especially for Black men, this journey is a present investment in my healing and my #BlackFuture. (Iâ€™ll probably get a few texts saying Iâ€™m being too emotional or sharing too much but I donâ€™t care. This is not weakness. ğŸ¤·ğŸ¾â€â™‚ï¸)
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
I believe that people often act without truly understanding their own intentions, their deeper motivations, and the internal trauma that results in external actions. Iâ€™m not perfect, so for me, that lack of understanding has affected the way I live, love, and lead. It shows up in insecurities, overthinking, depression, and stagnation. I donâ€™t list those things as trophies of suffering, but as context, as the pieces that make up my journey just as much as any of the rosier parts that are easier to handle.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
So my path to better #MentalHealth and trying #therapy means I first had to acknowledge those deeper roots I had not addressed. I had to understand the impact that people and the world have had on me, so that I can be more intentional with and aware of the impact that I have on the world and people around me. In order to make the world a better place, I have to start at home. #ItsOkNotToBeOk
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Just as with many other areas of growth, itâ€™s not an immediate transformation for me. Itâ€™s a process, an exploration of the space outside of my comfort zone. Itâ€™s a mindset that has to exist outside of my therapistâ€™s office, that supports my understanding of others and the challenges people face. The more I unpack my baggage, the more capacity I have to hold space and empathy with others as they walk similar roads.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Check the link in my bio to read a little bit more about my learning, as well as some of the role models speaking out, and tools people are creating to support. But I encourage you to figure out what works for you and give it a try. Itâ€™s well worth the exploration. There are tons of resources out there, and I'd love to hear what you do in order to build your mental strength as well!

My dadâ€™s 60th birthday is next week, and for the past couple weeks Iâ€™ve been thinking about how weâ€™re connected, about how his legacy continues through me.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
I love books and reading, and while it comes from both my parents, thereâ€™s a part of my dad that has stuck with me, this idea of learning never ending.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Growing up, we had a wall of bookshelves in our tiny apartment. Books on every subject, books of every size. When people would come over, or would see him reading something, my dad would let them borrow the book, give away the book, or buy another copy for them, sharing that knowledge and building connections through books.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Sharing a book is personal, telling someone that there are ideas you believe might be interesting or helpful or entertaining, sharing learning, sharing life experiences.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Iâ€™ve seen myself growing into that sharing, that legacy, so Iâ€™m giving away a few of my favorite books! These books are a collection of my childhood favorites, tools in my work and personal life, and a celebration of Black women authors.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Books:
-Children Of Blood and Bone (@tadeyemibooks) & Empathy (Roman Krznaric)
-Honey I Love (Eloise Greenfield) & Teaching Community (@bellhooks_)
-The Chronicles Of Narnia (CS Lewis) & Black Faces, White Spaces (Carolyn Finney)
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
RULES TO ENTER (US only):
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
1. Comment your favorite book and your takeaway/lesson from it.
2. For an extra entry, tag another book lover!
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €

Struggle is a part of life, and overcoming struggle a part of growth. That element of challenge is a big reason why I love climbing.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
The first time I ever went climbing, a few friends took me to Mazama. Now as a kid, I used to climb EVERYTHING (ask my mom). So I was preeetty confident this would be simple. I mean, Iâ€™m an athlete right?
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
I Thorâ€™d my way through a few routes (â€œANOTHER!â€), confidence right through the bright blue skies I was climbing under
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Then it hit. The route that wasnâ€™t straightforward, the mental/emotional baggage I hadnâ€™t beat yet, the challenge that wasnâ€™t like ones I had faced before, the tough semester in school or the semesters out of it, the hold/crimp that would force me out of my comfort zone
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
And I sat there.
I sat, strung up stories above the ground, arms pumped up and unable to drag me through, ready to quit. I asked to be let down (multiple times, and my friends didnâ€™t let me, literally and figuratively). So I sat. I sat, then tried, and sat, then tried something different. I sat, and cried (jk), and sat, then asked for advice
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Eventually, I made it to the top of that route (then they let me down). While I made it to the top this time, climbing is a reminder of those times in the middle, the struggle, the learning, the growth
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
So for those of you who are facing those sitting moments in life, the middle moments of your climb, I hope these reminders help you find your next hold:
- Itâ€™s ok to sit and not have a next move. Sometimes itâ€™s ok to pause and regain energy for what comes next
- Itâ€™s ok not to be strong all the time. Just like in climbing when you canâ€™t muscle through everything, strategy can help just as much as strength
- Itâ€™s ok to take what looks like a step back in order to move forward. Progress is not only measured at the end, but in the ste it takes to get there

What was your introduction to the outdoors?
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
This question is often asked in the outdoor recreation and environmental education fields, an effort to build common ground as people share the grounding experiences that inspired their love or connection to nature and the outdoors. Often these founding experiences are an adult introducing people to camping, first time canoeing/climbing, or family trips to national parks as a kid (if you were so lucky).
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Last year, the folks over at @brownenvironmentalist started a campaign to amplify the experiences, contributions and leadership of Black, Indigenous, and People of Color (BIPOC) in the environment. BE uses the hashtag #BeenOutside to â€œcelebrate the different and many ways that BIPOC have spent time in the outdoors for generations and throughout history, and how bipoc continue to enjoy time outside today.â€
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
As I look back and write my #BlackHistory, and tell the story of my connection to nature, I honor the fact that it was planted in me by my motherâ€™s fertilizer-soiled hands. As I look forward and write my #BlackFuture and my journey as an educator, I honor and realize that growth also has its roots in my grandmotherâ€™s #GouldingGardens. An educator, or anyone seeking to create lasting change in a community, has to live and teach with their mindset, the mindset of a gardener. Just as a gardener creates neither the seeds nor the soil that are in their garden, an educator organizes and brings together the resources available in their community. Just as the gardener tends to the environment surrounding the plants and their potential for growth, resilience, and sustainability, an educator also has to have a keen sense of awareness of the different factors that both block and encourage the growth of the young leaders or people they work with (in my case).
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €

Greensboro Four
February 1, 1960
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
David Richmond, Franklin McCain, Jibreel Khazan (Ezell Blair Jr.), Joe McNeil
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
When the students sat down at the "white only" counter of Woolworths they were told they would not be served. The police were called, but the Greensboro Four stayed until the store closed that day. The following day, twelve African Americans sat at the counter, and the protest grew.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
The group returned the next day with 25 men and four women and sat at the lunch counter from 11 a.m. until 3 p.m. enduring racist vitriol from the white customers. The students sat with their books ignoring the hecklers, according to reports by WFMY News.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
The Greensboro Four's act of courage inspired others. The Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee (SNCC) was founded in Raleigh, North Carolina, during the height of the sit-in protests in April 1960.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Their example has me thinking about how to spark change, how it takes courage and actions that go beyond words, how it means chipping away at the status quo, how it involves risk and potential sacrifice. Whatâ€™s my bold action? How do I show up and stand up for whatâ€™s right?
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
It also has me thinking of the impact we all can have. These four did not become national faces of the movement, they didnâ€™t become leaders who everyone followed. In some cases, they received backlash and had trouble finding jobs locally because of their stand. But their actions these few days were leadership in the sense that they inspired others to move towards change. Your actions, however small they might seem, have the same power. You donâ€™t have to be a charismatic, upfront, national public personality to lead and influence others. Put your hand to work with the skills you have and where you are, and we can change things together. âœŠğŸ¾

I donâ€™t lead because Iâ€™m perfect.
I lead because Iâ€™m not, and because I want my growth to be a collective journey.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â € â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
In all spaces, there is a desire for leadership. Not in the stereotypical sense of a charismatic person at a podium or someone with a fancy title who tells others what to do, but individuals who help to move a group towards a common goal. Some people donâ€™t believe that theyâ€™re leaders or influencers, butâ€¦
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Plot twist: If youâ€™re reading this itâ€™s too late. Youâ€™re a leader. No take backs.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
But leadership can be corrupted, most often by a scarcity mindset that causes people to think there can only be one, or it only looks a certain way, or that leadership is equal to popularity. It pops up even in spaces where people are trying to build/create community or affect positive change. Even with hashtags like #CommunityOverCompetition.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
That desire to be seen as a leader can lead people to build images of themselves that are polished and perfect, an image thatâ€™s more Beyonce â€œI woke up like thisâ€ than Drake â€œStarted from the bottom now we hereâ€. Itâ€™s missing the â€œThis is growth, Iâ€™m not what I used to be, Iâ€™ve made mistakes, this takes work.â€
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Iâ€™ve fallen into that trap too. But know that I have made mistakes in this journey and continue to grow. Iâ€™ve failed as a leader by not communicating with teammates and holding a vision in college clubs, by not setting an example of action or a structure with some of the trainings Iâ€™ve led. I fall victim to the jealousy/comparison bug just like anyone else. I grew up in a culture that was transphobic/homophobic, and though I am continually learning new traits, it means fighting through old ones that create exclusion. I have allowed my privilege to take up more space than is due, then been quiet as our patriarchal society makes certain parts of us feel like â€œothersâ€.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â € â €â €â €
So no, Iâ€™m not perfect. But I share this so that when you see me calling for change, you know where Iâ€™m coming from. Not from a desire to appear perfect, but an investment in myself and our community becoming more perfect by acknowledging faults and not being afraid to press forward.

I'm So (Lucky) Blessed
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Iâ€™d like to share part of an awesome conversation I had last week, and the meaning behind my favorite hat.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
It's a story of connection, the tale of a college dropout, a long line of blessings and the reason why I am intentional about being grateful for how people have invested in me and how I now do my best to pay it forward to others. (You can either read it here or at the link in my bio)
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
In 2011, I was hitting a wall, in the middle of failing out of school, unsure of where or how to move forward. In the middle of that frustration, trying to figure out what to do next, I checked my school email inbox for only the SECOND time while in school and saw an email for an internship seminar happening on campus that same day. My first internship and opportunity in this outdoor space came from that random thought.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
After that, some parts of life seemed to line up in my favor, and I used to heavily consider myself #lucky. I used to think that life happened to me and was beyond my control, and that it could just as easily be anyone else in my shoes. I shared that in a conversation with one of my mentors, and wondered how I could shape my next steps purposefully while feeling like luck had brought me this far.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
That conversation changed how I viewed my progress, my life (read the blog post for what he said). I stopped chalking up any #success to pure luck, and instead started to count my #blessings. I started to be grateful and acknowledge the blessing of people who had invested in me, started appreciating the passion and hard work I put in, and thanking God for his covering through all the ups and downs.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Besides the mindset of gratitude for the past, appreciation of present moments, the shift to blessings put me in a position to pay it forward.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
You canâ€™t pass forward luck, but when youâ€™re blessed, you have the opportunity to hold the door open for someone else behind you. Your cup of blessings can overflow to bless other people in your life.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
So no, Iâ€™m not lucky, Iâ€™m #blessed. And now I wear this hat so I donâ€™t forget, and as a reminder to be a blessing to others.

STANDING WITH THE GWICHâ€™IN
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
From the Gwichâ€™in:
â€œThe Arctic National Wildlife Refuge is one of the wildest, intact remaining landscapes in the world; supporting the 200,000 strong porcupine caribou herd and migratory birds from all fifty states and six continents. The Gwichâ€™in Nation depends on the coastal plain, the biological heart of the Refuge, for our way of life. At this moment where this place and our people who depend on it are under attack from the Trump Administration, we must band together and show our solidarity and unwillingness to back down. We will celebrate our homelands and ask for our partners and allies nationwide to join together to do the same; standing with the Gwichâ€™in Nation and knowing we also stand with you in communities across the world. This fight is all of our fights; and your fight is ours.â€
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Companies have applied for permits to conduct seismic testing for oil in the Refuge, also known as the â€œSacred Place Where Life Beginsâ€. The reality of seismic testing is brutal -- their 90,000-lb â€œthumper trucksâ€ would send shock waves deep into the ground, carving tracks into the tundra and disturbing polar bear dens. And they could start as early as this month.

Hands that held eight children and fifteen grandchildren.

Hands that daily and faithfully crack open her Bible and Sabbath School lesson.
Hands that cooked meals.
Hands of a matriarch, hands of a wife.
Hands that no longer plant flowers and draw life from the ground but prick fingers to draw blood, to draw life.
The hands that my hands stem from.

18. I hug random people. For fun.
19. I'm a Knicks fan. It teaches faith and perseverance.
20. I'm horrible at taking compliments. Not used to getting them. I always doubt that they're real.
21. I love causing trouble and being different. Fight me.
